<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="440" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,506,1431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1190,1215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath" authorityName="Viraktamath" box="[662,1026,1190,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Xenovarta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ankusha">
<emphasis box="[662,880,1190,1214]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">Xenovarta ankusha</emphasis>
Viraktamath
</taxonomicName>
in having the aedeagal shaft twisted at mid length, slightly arched in lateral aspect; its subapex with a process; and gonopore subapical. It can be distinguished from the latter by the aedeagal shaft with a lamellar subapical process, approximately sickle-shaped; style apophysis fingerlike and without transverse rugulae; pygofer side with middle of dorsal margin and ventral margin strongly inflexed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="440" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,506,1431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1370,1395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is derived from the Latin words “ 
<taxonomicName box="[1019,1097,1371,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Xenovarta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcata">
<emphasis box="[1019,1097,1371,1395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="440">falcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, indicating the subapical of aedeagal shaft with a sickle-shaped process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
